explanation: When I set the n_steps to 16 (in run 19) I did not get the minimum bic, so I am setting the n_steps back to 1 (which was the case in run 18 and I had gotten the min bic) and checking if doing that makes me get the min bic again or if it was just based on chance how the model explored. I will be testing if my code can recover the DAG rather than an ADMG by using linear gaussian data for the DAG with equal variances to ensure that the DAG is identifiable. I am using 10 nodes, 2 degree - to make things simpler, 2000 samples, 20_000 steps_per_env, 8 envs, n_step = 16 (as opposed to 1 in run 18 - that is the only difference). Single run, just to check. using a higher threshold as per the ALIAS paper of 0.3. Use the commit 61e3568bbeb69c85ce9004540d49fb145dacd31f as a reference to revert back. I will be modifying some core files of the project before running the code - since it needs to find a DAG. In the params I am adding admg_model key since the admg finding function expects it not because it is required - since we are deadling with a DAG here. I have set verbose to 1 so that I can see the progress being made. Even when I used 8000 steps per env the result was the same - the predicted BIC was just about a 100 larger than the true BIC - how the fuck is that possible.
